text:
para reporter memilih 6 kontroversi paling buruk sepanjang tahun 2018
#
2018 adalah tahun dengan berbagai skandal di k-entertainment dengan banyak masalah kontroversial, tuntutan hukum, dan banyak lagi. sekarang dengan hanya beberapa minggu tersisa di tahun ini, wartawan dari sports today menyimpulkan orang-orang terburuk dengan kontroversi terburuk pada tahun 2018. siapa yang menurut para wartawan adalah yang terburuk tahun ini? lihatlah daftar di bawah ini: 1. yang hyun suk: pembatalan debut 'mixnine' "dengan kekuatan yg sebagai agensi, dia mengatakan dia akan membuat debut dan menempatkan peserta pelatihan dalam kompetisi, tetapi membatalkan debut mereka karena program itu gagal. dia menciptakan kontroversi dengan menanggapi geliat terakhir mereka mengambil tindakan hukum dengan gugatan balik. kemudian bahkan setahun kemudian, dia menciptakan acara audisi yang sama 'yg treasure box.' ide ironisnya mengejutkan semua orang. " - reporter yoon hye young. 2. lee seo won: pelecehan seksual "tingkah lakunya yang berani setelah pelecehan seksual, ketidaktahuan terus-menerus, dan terakhir, tindakan melarikan diri ke militer. aku terkejut 3 kali." - reporter kim sat byul 3. kim saeng min: #metoo "dia menghabiskan waktu emas yang ditunggu-tunggu dalam 25 tahun. kamu mendapatkan apa yang kamu berikan." - reporter kim na yeon 4. nancy lang x wang: pernikahan dan perceraian yang kontroversial "pembuat masalah dengan perkawinan, perkelahian, dan perceraian yang gaduh." - reporter han ye ji 5. lee jin min cp: manipulasi 'heart signal 2' "dia menciptakan program viral 'heart signal' tetapi ada juga banyak kontroversi. dia bahkan lebih mengecewakan penonton dengan perilakunya yang tidak menyenangkan dalam wawancara tentang kesalahan siaran, manipulasi dalam penyuntingan, dan banyak lagi." - reporter moon soo yeon 6. microdot: kasus lenipuan orang tua "orang tuanya berbohong kepada orang-orang di kota mereka, putranya berbohong kepada pemirsa." - reporter kim hyun min source : allkpop, oh_mestrans by : pinkÂ©ksense
link: https://koreanarea.com/2018/12/23/para-reporter-memilih-6-kontroversi-paling-buruk-sepanjang-tahun-2018/

text:
hey girl, how you doin? ğŸ˜˜ğŸ˜‚ğŸ¤˜
i dont think you understand my excitement for this shirt. 
1. the money went to some friends awesome band(heartbreaker, it was camp dad's last show) 
2. its comfy as hell 
3. its purple(i have top colors, no favorites, and purples a top color) 
4. i am awkward often. it makes some think i do not like them, it makes some think i'm stuck up, it makes some think i'm on drugs, it makes some think...well we all know theres only a wee bit of me that gives a fuck what others think. haha 
i love supporting local artists, hopefully inget my id figured out soon. i needed this so badly. tshirts(i rarely wear them haha must be meaningful or from a memorable experience), photos, and live music are my jam. getting out to shows is really helping parts of me come out that i keep locked away. except the awkward part, that flies freely and out of control quite often. haha when i left the first thing i did on my own was go out to some local live music. it felt so fucking amazing, and feels just as amazing every time. ğŸ˜Š wait what am i talking about again?? haha ğŸ˜‰ #awkward #awkwardaf #queer #survivor #blog #blogger #inspire #30anddivorced #living #love #happy #lgbtq #recovery #sobriety #bebold #bebrave #beyou #metoo #punk #punkrock #campdad #lifetransformation #findingme #mystory #selflove #selfcare #idgaf #notalady

a couple new pieces on the 'ol bloggy doggy! i have art just pouring out of me these days and i love it. i love writing my thoughts, woes, poetry, and of course my letters... there's inspiration everywhere. positive and negative. i feel very moved to make some sort of change to make things better more than ever. not just in my life and the lives of those close to me, but in the whole world. cliche, i know, but i wish to make my mark even if only one person is inspired to do better. text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: âœ–ï¸girls talkâœ–ï¸ ffion. radio dj, promoter and writer. .
1.5 oz. terroir gin (@stgeorgespirits)
3/4 oz. lillet blanc (@lillet)
3/4 oz. green chartreuse
1/2 oz. mint syrup
3 dashes cascade celery bitters (@bittered_sling)
.
so i finally got myself a st. george spirits bottle for the home bar. of all their products, this is the one i've seen recommended the most, and after just sipping the terroir gin, i can see why it's so well-loved! it's remarkably distinct in a cocktail, but can also be enjoyed equally (or even more) on it's own.
.
the botanicals include douglas fir, california bay laurel, coastal sage, among other "evocative" botanicals. i thought cascade celery bitters would be the perfect companion for a gin which boasts aromas of evergreen forests.
.
which st. george spirits bottle should i try for next?

text:
pandan punch
.
2 oz. reposado tequila (@casamigos)
1/4 oz. vida mezcal (@delmagueymezcal)
1 oz. lime juiceÂ 
3/4 oz. pandan syrup
1/4 oz. china china (bigallet1872)
2 dashes moondog bitters (bittered_sling)
1 oz. whole milk (to clarify)
garnish with fresh pandan leaf
multiply recipe for desired number of servings
.
okay, last clarified milk punch for a while (but no promises). i was glad to finally find a piece of glassware like this available on amazon, and figured it was the perfect vessel to serve a milk punch in. if you're looking for some additional resources on how to go about making a milk punch,Â @barfaith has an instagram story highlight on the process, andÂ @cocktailchemistry also just put up a video detailing milk punches. check 'em out!
.
as for the cocktail above, the reposado tequila provided a sweet, smooth base, with a touch of smoke provided by mezcal. pandan syrup for that round, almost coconut-y sweetness. lime juice for acidity and clarification. china china for complexity, and moondog bitters for a spicy element. for the choice of reposado tequila i opted for casamigos, with its honeyed notes of caramel and vanilla working well with the fragrant pandan syrup.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

evawiâ€™s website states: â€˜start by believingâ€™ is a philosophy that should guide our responses to sexual assault. it â€œflips the scriptâ€ on the message victims have historically received from professionals and support people, which is: â€œhow do i know youâ€™re not lying?â€ if someone discloses to you, start by believing them. listen, support, and help locate resources if needed. you can make the difference to one personâ€™s healing. 
we can believe in due process and support survivors. .
.

.

you only gonna get this at the freeport academy. you can't watch mgtow videos and learn the pillow talk red pills. if it's too tough, motts has prefilled red pilled apple sauce for you.

men don't realize how many divorces happen after home renovations. these articles will say the stress of renovations leads to divorce.

i remember having a conversation with a married woman. we had just finished fucking and her husband was blowing up her phone. she starts talking shit about him and how she can't wait to divorce after the home is done.

i asked "what do you mean after the home is done"? she told me they had started renovations in the home at her request. she jokingly told me, he wants to do anything he can to keep the marriage alive and he did this to try and make her feel a bit happier about the marriage.

side note - a marriage is directly tied to the home in many cases. coming home to a house you don't love will carry on to the marriage because the core of your marriage, memories and experiences, take place at home.

back to the game, i asked "if you still planned on divorcing him why did you let him do the he renovations" and she said because he is putting about 50k into the renovation of the kitchen and bathrooms, so it will make the value of the house go up, which means she gets more money when she divorces him and sells the home.

keep in mind this woman was in her late 40s and i was in early 20s, so i been had the red pills early. this is why i say men need to date older women and cougars cuz you will learn how women feel for real during marriage. a young bitch is still in her fantasy land stage. the cougars are way more realistic and gave marriage battles scars that have healed 10 times over.

as i always say if you have only been a lifetime boyfriend or husband you don't know women. i have learned little motives and manipulation tactics from plenty of women that have been married longer than i have been alive. 
women check out years before the husband even figured out the marriage was in trouble. renovations won't save your marriage nor will a second wedding or new car. its just more money and assets for her to gain in the divorce.

you only gonna get this at the freeport academy. you can not watch mgtow videos and learn the pillow talk red pills. if it is too tough, motts has prefilled red pilled apple sauce for you.

men do not realize how many divorces happen after home renovations. these articles will say the stress of renovations leads to divorce.

i remember having a conversation with a married woman. we had just finished fucking and her husband was blowing up her phone. she starts talking shit about him and how she can not wait to divorce after the home is done.

i asked "what do you mean after the home is done"? she told me they had started renovations in the home at her request. she jokingly told me, he wants to do anything he can to keep the marriage alive and he did this to try and make her feel a bit happier about the marriage.

side note - a marriage is directly tied to the home in many cases. coming home to a house you do not love will carry on to the marriage because the core of your marriage, memories and experiences, take place at home.

back to the game, i asked "if you still planned on divorcing him why did you let him do the he renovations" and she said because he is putting about 50k into the renovation of the kitchen and bathrooms, so it will make the value of the house go up, which means she gets more money when she divorces him and sells the home.

keep in mind this woman was in her late 40s and i was in early 20s, so i been had the red pills early. this is why i say men need to date older women and cougars cuz you will learn how women feel for real during marriage. a young bitch is still in her fantasy land stage. the cougars are way more realistic and gave marriage battles scars that have healed 10 times over.

as i always say if you have only been a lifetime boyfriend or husband you do not know women. i have learned little motives and manipulation tactics from plenty of women that have been married longer than i have been alive. 
women check out years before the husband even figured out the marriage was in trouble. renovations will not save your marriage nor will a second wedding or new car. its just more money and assets for her to gain in the divorce.

text:
#breaking story from zimbabweâ€”five victims at risk of being trafficked intercepted at busy bus station in harare!â €
â €
our staff noticed five young people grouped together at a large bus station. they caught the attention of our staff because they appeared to be nervous and hesitant. our staff decided to approach and ask the travelers some questions. but a man appeared and started answering on behalf of the travelers.â €
â €
he also was in possession of one, if not more, of their passports. due to these red flags, our staff intervened and involved local police in securing the interception. due to the ongoing war in their home country, the girls were unable to return to there, so our staff coordinated their temporary placement in a refugee camp in harare. â €
â €
learn more about our work in zimbabwe at the link in bio. #zimbabwe #lovejusticeâ €

text:
you can find red pills anywhere. when i read and watch financial reports, i get more reasons not to get married than watching mgtow videos.

many men seem to think of women as angels and that's their downfall. you should view them as calculating, manipulative women that have an agenda and end game. all women have a place they want to be. that place doesn't include anyone else but themselves. the man makes 50 year plans and imagines living retired in paris with his kids in college and his wife and him running a business.

the woman imagines living retired in paris, so her whole life will be directed towards her end game.

women will think in pragmatic terms when marrying, unlike the stupid male. the man marries the romantic idealism of marriage while the woman marries the business side of it.

as it pertains to debt, in many states the debt is combined along with all the finances and assets. so it comes down to what you invested and your return on investment. marriage must be looked at as an investment more than just a business.

a woman can come into a marriage with no property, 1 kid, 400k debt and a 30k salary. let's say she marries a guy that is older has no kids, 1 home 80k debt and a 100 salary. in a divorce they will combine debt her 400k + his 80k. then split it in half if it is a community property state. so they will both have to play 240k of debt in case of divorce. the same happens with a home, if there is 200k on a house, they will have to split that.

so many women will wait until the husband pays off the house or pays all the debt and then leave him. the other way is she comes in with more debt and leaves with her debt partially paid plus him getting half of it in divorce. if a woman has 400k debt and the man has zero. he will be paying some of it off during the marriage and then will have to split the rest after divorce. so it's a win win for the woman.

on top of the debt being paid, she will get the home, child support (for the kids he didn't create) and alimony based on what he made. since most professional men downgrade when marrying (marry hot broke women, with less than them) they get screwed over.

text:
final master project performance costume. 
if i am dead: he killed me :is intended to tell the story of a friend. she married a man she loved and her life descended into hell. the psychological, verbal and emotional abuse he tormented her with changed who she was fundamentally. she became what he made her into, a woman who no one would believe, listen to or help. she is left with ptsd, which is forever and keeps her from telling her story. the ptsd has scarred her permanently, and drastically effects everything. 
i share her story in memory of the girl, this woman once was, the girl who taught me how to be strong. even now as â€˜damagedâ€™ as she thinks she is, continues to teach me what true strength and the kindness of the human soul really means.

credits:
photos by emmi hyyppÃ¤
concept and realization by: dee gowans
performance by: @simonelabarga and luke biaco
choreographed by: @petalily 
produced by @agnestreplin for @lcflondon_ @unioftheartslondon 
lighting design by antony hateley
sound design by wilfred petherbridge
hair and makeup by @goshkamuah 
the most amazing technician in the world (you were right!!!): marion yarwood
thanks to: claire christie, donatella barbieri

a massive thank you to @ak liee who not only was my emotional support, but also for being my stage manager during all my chaotic rehearsals.
also thank you to @lina_aly and @oliver.to for steaming the dress for me, as well as @nashwamaatouk and oliver , for cleaning the stage of those flower petals. 
one last thank you to the amazing @julievholm , who not only had to deal with me when i was at my worst and made me laugh every chance she got, she is basically hercules. but who also helped me with many elements of testing my costume ideas and helping me sew the loops closed during the most sleep deprived hours of my life. amazing human, performer and friend.

#lcf #costume #costumedesign #metoo #domesticviolence #domesticviolenceawareness #ptsdawareness #ptsd #verbalabuse #timesup #emotionalabuse #weddingdress #wedding #applique #beading

text:
.
i am so sorry.
that my needs are my priority.
i'm sorry that i have boundaries.
and you won't always get what you want from me.
maybe many years of overgiving,
have finally made me cheap.
with my time,
my affection,
and my flexibility.
i'm sorry i can't entertain you,
and refuse to put on a show.
i'm sorry that after all this time,
i am finally saying no.
after many years of holding on,
i'm okay now with letting go.
and i'm sorry that i'm not sorry,
for prioritizing my growth.

text:
so we often adopt the notion that for change to be valid, it must always be grand. we burden ourselves with the expectation that we must turn our lives around overnight. we disregard the â€œlittleâ€ things that we can do and instead choose to focus on the same go big or go home mentality that frankly keeps us stuck in our mundane ways more often than we care to admit.because breaking out of your comfort zone is not just making a drastic change and wishing for the best. itâ€™s freeing yourself from the rigid cognitive beliefs you hold about yourself and how your life is â€œsupposedâ€ to be lived. itâ€™s gaining flexibility and becoming more open to the possibility that life is ultimately a series of endless ones. sometimes, itâ€™s as simple as realizing that there is nothing really comfortable about your â€œcomfort zoneâ€ after all...

text:
final master project performance costume. 
if i am dead: he killed me :is intended to tell the story of a friend. she married a man she loved and her life descended into hell. the psychological, verbal and emotional abuse he tormented her with changed who she was fundamentally. she became what he made her into, a woman who no one would believe, listen to or help. she is left with ptsd, which is forever and keeps her from telling her story. the ptsd has scarred her permanently, and drastically effects everything. 
i share her story in memory of the girl, this woman once was, the girl who taught me how to be strong. even now as â€˜damagedâ€™ as she thinks she is, continues to teach me what true strength and the kindness of the human soul really means.

credits:
photos by emmi hyyppÃ¤
concept and realization by: dee gowans
performance by: @simonelabarga and luke biaco
choreographed by: @petalily 
produced by @agnestreplin for @lcflondon_ @unioftheartslondon 
lighting design by antony hateley
sound design by wilfred petherbridge
hair and makeup by @goshkamuah 
the most amazing technician in the world (you were right!!!): marion yarwood
thanks to: claire christie, donatella barbieri

a massive thank you to @ak liee who not only was my emotional support, but also for being my stage manager during all my chaotic rehearsals.
also thank you to @lina_aly and @oliver.to for steaming the dress for me, as well as @nashwamaatouk and oliver , for cleaning the stage of those flower petals. 
one last thank you to the amazing @julievholm , who not only had to deal with me when i was at my worst and made me laugh every chance she got, she is basically hercules. but who also helped me with many elements of testing my costume ideas and helping me sew the loops closed during the most sleep deprived hours of my life. amazing human, performer and friend.

#lcf #costume #costumedesign #metoo #domesticviolence #fightlikeagirl #notallbruisescanbeseen #notallbruisesarevisible #domesticviolenceawareness #ptsdawareness #ptsd #verbalabuse #timesup #weddingdress #wedding #applique #beading

final master project performance costume. 
if i am dead: he killed me :is intended to tell the story of a friend. she married a man she loved and her life descended into hell. the psychological, verbal and emotional abuse he tormented her with changed who she was fundamentally. she became what he made her into, a woman who no one would believe, listen to or help. she is left with ptsd, which is forever and keeps her from telling her story. the ptsd has scarred her permanently, and drastically effects everything. 
i share her story in memory of the girl, this woman once was, the girl who taught me how to be strong. even now as â€˜damagedâ€™ as she thinks she is, continues to teach me what true strength and the kindness of the human soul really means.

also thank you to @lina_aly and @oliver.to for steaming the dress for me, as well as @nashwamaatouk and oliver , for cleaning the stage of those flower petals. 
one last thank you to the amazing @julievholm , who not only had to deal with me when i was at my worst and made me laugh every chance she got, she is basically hercules. but who also helped me with many elements of testing my costume ideas and helping me sew the loops closed during the most sleep deprived hours of my life. amazing human, performer and friend.

text:
// musician offers new way to cope with trauma //
â €â €
recent headlines are unearthing immense collective trauma. some folks are finally telling their stories of sexual assault after years of keeping the experiences to themselves. it only makes sense that trauma stored within our bodies can have physical effects.
â €â €
amber field â€“ an sf-based vocal coach, musician, and artivist â€“ pays careful attention to these somatic effects in their work with sound and movement.
â €â €
field says the term â€œdarvoâ€ â€“ coined by jennifer freyd â€“ is a helpful approach to thinking about kavanaugh and the culture of sexual assault.
â €â €
darvo stands for â€œdeny, attack, and reverse victim and offender.â€ in essence, offenders often deflect responsibility by ping-ponging the blame back onto the victim. this is where self-blame and internalized trauma can grow. but by identifying the process and understanding how to detach and release themselves from this type of emotional manipulation, victims and people surrounding them can find ways to move forward.
â €â €
field believes that physical movement and sound are incredibly helpful in releasing this trauma.
â €â €
â€œdarvo was an enlightening approach that gave me insight into the experience of women,â€ field told new sincerity. â€œand within our culture this was an opportunity to decide where to go next.â€
â €â €

recent headlines are unearthing immense collective trauma. some folks are finally telling their stories of sexual assault after years of keeping the experiences to themselves. it only makes sense that trauma stored within our bodies can have physical effects.
â €â €
amber field â€“ an sf-based vocal coach, musician, and artivist â€“ pays careful attention to these somatic effects in their work with sound and movement.
â €â €
field says the term â€œdarvoâ€ â€“ coined by jennifer freyd â€“ is a helpful approach to thinking about kavanaugh and the culture of sexual assault.
â €â €
darvo stands for â€œdeny, attack, and reverse victim and offender.â€ in essence, offenders often deflect responsibility by ping-ponging the blame back onto the victim. this is where self-blame and internalized trauma can grow. but by identifying the process and understanding how to detach and release themselves from this type of emotional manipulation, victims and people surrounding them can find ways to move forward.
â €â €
field believes that physical movement and sound are incredibly helpful in releasing this trauma.

text:
last night started out as the perfect summer night.beach,friends,snacks&even fire dancing lessons.this perfect summer night had different plans for us,though.
as my friends&i left clifton 2nd,one of us heard struggling under the trees near the steps,where the hired chairs were stacked.as we reached closer we realised we were disturbing a man who was assaulting a woman sexually.
he bolted,realising heâ€™d been caught&to his surprise was stopped by not one woman, but two.this,although commendable,is not the point.
as some of my friends ran to catch this disgusting excuse for a human being,i fought through the chairs&bush to get to the woman who was left behind.this was while she,the real fighter,fought with what was left in her,to get to the only help that came. 
though she was a stranger,it was horrific to see her like that.what started,for her,as an innocent stroll on the beach with a boy,ended with her being dragged to a place where she was changed from a summer lover,into a victim of sexual violence.
caught up in this â€˜dramaâ€™ was my friendâ€™s 14yr old daughter.who like me,is a water baby.because of this one moment out of a million moments at one of her favourite places,she is ambivalent about going back,because of the association to this incident.not because she is unaware,like most of us,that â€˜these things happenâ€™.she is afraid because in a crowd of almost 200 people,no one helped until they saw other people doing so first. 
we were cautious,to become too involved.i guess you could say we instinctively remembered that in this sometimes ugly world-humility,bravery&kindness will always be needed.by you&by others. 
while there were respectable men with us,that contributed to diffusing this terrible situation,last night it was the women who chased the guy down.the women,(& teenage girl),that held it together&made sure we all made it out safely.that called the cops.that had no choice but to be brave enough to trust a stranger to lead them to safety.that proved to a young girl that doing whatâ€™s right will always be more important than being silent. 
itâ€™s respect for ourselves&each other as women,as humans,that will lead us along the path to â€˜salvationâ€™.

text:
if you grew up in a family of abuse, and the abuser(s) are still there, then staying away from being with family over the holidays can be one of the most difficult decisions to make and stick to.
.
for some, holidays were the only "good times" - meaning, the only times when abuse wasn't taking place. thus, it's very easy for a survivor to glorify the holidays into this magical space where it's as if the abuse never existed, and also believe that the family you experience on that day is the only reality. but, unfortunately, the truth is that image is the furthest thing from reality.
.
this can be especially difficult to wrap your mind around if the abuse has occurred since you were a child. your brain's understanding of the world and family, was forming in the midst of these abusive relationship(s).
.
#traumabonding is a common thing to develop in those environments. even though you may be in a place today where part of you knows what your abuser(s) have done (or are doing) is wrong, you can still find yourself confused and tied to this idea that you are supposed to be with them over the holidays.
.
this makes the decision to stay away all the harder and so confusing.
.
my assault was not by a family member, but i have worked with survivors who that is their story. some are able to clearly see their abuser(s) for who they are, and others find it confusing to see them clearly.
.
abuse is about having power over someone else. it's about control. taking steps to physically distance yourself is so important to break that power, but so is emotional and mental distance.
.
survivors who have been able to break trauma bonds often say the turning point was when they decided to let the "dream" die of what their relationship with their abuser(s) could be. dreams that one day they'll stop, apologize, all will be okay.
.
**see the 2 comments below for the rest of this post**
.

text:
last night, the wizard of oz was on tv. itâ€™s been one of my favorite movies since i was old enough to even have a favorite movie.
.
i tried to watch it, but i couldnâ€™t. just hearing the cowardly lionâ€™s initial growl made me feel sick, and thatâ€™s where i finally stopped watching.
.
but this morning, i found a few director gifts that some actors gave me when we produced wizard of oz in august. and it reminded me of all the amazing, beautiful, talented, smart, kind people i worked with on this show. and it made me fall in love with wizard of oz in a new, refreshing, and powerful way.
.
@gizmo1198 made me belly laugh at every. single. rehearsal. she gave my heart much-needed laughter and joy this summer. there is power in making people laugh, and she has a very special gift.
.
@ofsunrays made me proud to be a woman and an actor. who cares whether a man or woman plays the scarecrow? ella was the best actor for the role. she didnâ€™t just â€œpull it off.â€ she nailed it. if she can do something hard, different, and unexpected, then so can i.
.
@aprilshowersrn helped me get through that show. without her, i may not still be here today and wizard of oz wouldnâ€™t have happened. and yet, she was my glinda, who made me realize i had the power all along. i just had to learn it myself.
.
@thedeez gave me words of wisdom and kindness that equally helped me remember that i am brave and strong. no matter how weak and helpless i was feeling, i must have been doing something right in order for people to see me as inspiring and a good role model.
.
@s.ydneybush and i got to share the honor of performing with bravo in the final scene of his last show as an animal actor. i couldnâ€™t have asked for a better â€œstage nieceâ€ to share in the reminder that i do have courage, that i will get my dogs back from that â€œwicked old witch,â€ and that â€œthere is no place like home.â€
.

i rediscovered that â€œhomeâ€ is with my mom, dad, sister, nephews, and grandparents. i finally have that home again just in time for christmas. iâ€™ve often wondered why they play the wizard of oz in december, but iâ€™m so thankful they do ğŸ’–
.
.
.
.
.

text:
not only do i love what i do but it's also the why that i do it.  i love what this company is about and how we all contribute to a wonderful cause.

younique was founded in 2012 with creating funding for the younique foundation as its ultimate goalâ€”and as the fastest-growing direct sales company in history, younique succeeded enough to make that dream a reality within two short years. 
with so many women part of the #metoo movement and unaware that this part of our company even exists, i wanted them to know there are people out there who actually care and want to help you. 
the haven retreat brings healing and hope to sexually abused women, is completely free (aside from travel), and is at an undisclosed location in utah, but theyâ€™re in the process of opening a second facility. we have products that 100% of the proceeds goes directly toward the younique foundation, and you can also round up your order to the nearest dollar. 
if you or someone you know was sexually abused before the age of 18, and they want more info, you can go to youniquefoundation.org.

the victims who attend the retreat are kept anonymous, and you do not have to be a presenter to attend. ğŸ’œ

text:
sending someone a card, not an email, a physical card or letter  has becoming less and less popular. now the mailbox stands for business or loneliness. waiting was no longer a virtue to be praised and we are becoming less patient. i want to say that â€œi love youâ€œ but i fear if those words have never travelled far through the wind and rain, can they withstand the quandary of which other people, ambition and bad timing might stand in the way. so i write letters still. each one of them is a wish/prayer i sent to myself. i say â€œi love youâ€ in inky letters sealed in envelopes. i send them away and wait. counting days to see if i can learn the trick of self love before my past send me hugs in poetry. |#jin_daily #iwriteletterstomyself #sflife #mailbox #writersofinstagram

text:
its biblical. .
really though.  its ok to test them occasionally. .
your daughters will be shoved out into a world that despite your best preparations, can be crap.  bullies, school shootings, "#metoo" and so much more.  so much more than we could ever imagine.  pressures and situations that we as fathers have never been exposed to. .
build resilient girls.  build future women who understand their worth and are not afraid to stand firm in their faith.  women who will stand tall with a humble strength and vicious tenacity.  lead them well so they will understand how to lead others in times of turbulence.
.
most importantly, teach them how to huck a mean cannonball.

text:
tarcâ€™s ride to safety program provides free transportation for anyone who needs to get to the center for women and families.

simply get onto any tarc bus in louisville or southern indiana and tell the driver you need a ride to safety. you do not need money or a tarc ticket; the ride is free. the driver will arrange for a tarc employee to meet the bus somewhere on its route who will transport you in a car to the center for women and families. you can use this free service if youâ€™re by yourself or if you have your children with you.

for information on tarc stops and routes, visit www.ridetarc.org or pick-up a route schedule at one of the many information stands across louisville and southern indiana.

for more information about the center for women and families and the ride to safety program, call our toll-free crisis line at 1-844-237-2331.

"as the #metoo movement evolved over the last year and a half,Â it has mostly been photographers who have been #cancelled from fashion industryâ€™s ranks. but earlier this month, street casting practices came into questionÂ after a 16-year-old boy accused russian streetwear designer gosha rubchinskiy of soliciting nude photos via instagram and the messaging platform whatsapp."
*
"while someÂ (if not many) modeling agenciesÂ have a disconcerting past when it comes to safeguarding modelsâ€™ well-being, street castingâ€”which includesÂ instagram casting as far as the 2010s are concernedâ€”is muddied by its own set of ethical issues."

i'm up to something new in #2019 . i'm ready for new people, new activities, new hobbies and places. 2018 was a fantastic year, i found my place and my #destiny (at least i hope so). thank you all.
you don't have to risk it all, but you have to move on, no matter what.
p.s. don't judge a book by it's cover. even if it's a fancy cover.

why the pope was never affected by the #metoo movement? 
romeâ€”pope francis on friday capped a year of sex-abuse scandals in the catholic church by vowing to â€œdo all that is necessaryâ€ to punish abusers for their â€œabominationsâ€ and urging the guilty to turn themselves in. â€œto those who abuse minors, i would say this: convert and hand yourself over to human justice, and prepare for divine justice,â€ the pope told vatican officials.

text:
2018 adalah tahun skandal lainnya di k-entertainment dengan banyak masalah kontroversial tuntutan hukum, dan banyak lagi.

dengan hanya beberapa minggu tersisa di tahun ini, wartawan dari sports today memilih orang-orang terburuk dengan kontroversi terburuk pada tahun 2018. siapa yang menurut para wartawan adalah yang terburuk tahun ini? lihatlah daftar di bawah ini.

1. yang hyun suk: pembatalan debut 'mixnine'
"dengan kekuatan yg sebagai tiang, dia mengatakan akan mendebutkan dan menempatkan trainee dalam kompetisi. namun ia membatalkan debut mereka karena program itu gagal. dia menciptakan kontroversi dengan menanggapinya dengan mengambil tindakan hukum lewat gugatan balik. kemudian bahkan setahun kemudian, ia menciptakan acara audisi yang sama 'yg treasure box.' ide ironisnya mengejutkan semua orang. " - reporter yoon hye young.

2. lee seo won: pelecehan seksual
"tingkah lakunya yang berani setelah pelecehan seksual, ketidaktahuan terus-menerus, dan terakhir, tindakannya melarikan diri ke militer. aku terkejut 3 kali." - reporter kim sat byul

3. kim saeng min: #metoo
"dia menghabiskan waktu emas yang ditunggu-tunggu dalam 25 tahun. kau mendapatkan apa yang kamu berikan." - reporter kim na yeon

4. nancy lang x wang: pernikahan dan perceraian yang kontroversial
"pembuat masalah dengan perkawinan, perkelahian, dan perceraian yang gaduh." - reporter han ye ji

5 lee jin min cp: manipulasi 'heart signal 2' "dia menciptakan program viral 'heart signal' tetapi ada juga banyak kontroversi. dia bahkan lebih mengecewakan penonton dengan perilakunya yang tidak menyenangkan dalam wawancara tentang kesalahan siaran, manipulasi dalam penyuntingan, dan banyak lagi." - reporter moon soo yeon

6. microdot: penipuan orang tua
"orang tuanya berbohong kepada orang-orang di kota mereka, putranya berbohong kepada pemirsa." - reporter kim hyun min

bagaimana menurut kalian?

#koreanesia

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
according to a study conducted in the us, the #metoo movement encouraged by alyssa milano has contributed to a shift in public thinking about sexual harassment. the movement, in case you don't know, took off following public accusations of sexual harassment and assault against film producer harvey weinstein.
the researchers noted that the overall volume of google searches originating for this particular topic was 86 percent higher during the last eight months than what it could have been in the absence of #metoo. apparently, there were 40 to 54 million google searches related to sexual harassment or assault, which happens to be the greatest number of searches on this topic ever recorded in the u.s.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i stumbled upon this interesting article about an ongoing debate in us over classic holiday song â€œbaby itâ€™s cold outsideâ€. apparently, some people consider it has a â€œrapey lyricâ€. with radio stations and media outlets avoiding to air the song to prevent negative reactions, some even publicly banned it from their playlist. .

controversy over the song rise as a result of the #meetoo movement. a movement that aims to fight sexual violence against women that grew popular in recent year. .

while i do support the main aims of the #meetoo movement, i just think this is far fetched.
the song has been aired since 1944, originally written & performed by a married couple. dean martin, ella fitzgerald, & countless artist including michael buble did a cover on the song. have you heard the lyrics? i made a small polls asking my friends about this and 75% of them agreed that the song is fine. to me the song is cheeky, but itâ€™s definitely not rapey. if anything itâ€™s just a couple who passive aggressively flirting!

i do understand the importance of advocating & listening to the experiences of the abused, but in my humble opinion #metoo movement need to curate their focus better to maintain their credibility as a movement. 
________________________________________

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
@ghosthunterthemovie love seeing this in stores! have you seen #ghosthuntermovie yet? a glimpse into my life..a massive branch from a tree who has grown many experiencing many highs and lows throughout my life. people wonder how i survived but truth is i just thought that's what life was about. i was accustomed to survival from a very young age so even the struggles after the original trauma just seemed like normal life. i'm nearly 46 and i'm only learning of my cptsd in the past few years. it's so refreshing to understand that i'm not just crazy that my brain has conditioned me to fight or flight responses.  ox never be afraid to speak up and ask for help. you are honestly never alone. so many people suffer in silence and there is no need xo
love and light xoxox hope you all have a very merry xmas and safe happy new year xoxox

text:
2018 has been a bitch.
i don't want to hold this speech as deep as a plot to an amature gay porn but.. i got to know so many people and also my career has improved through events like one when guns n roses shared my cover from their song estranged. it was a crazy feeling to know that people see something unique in you and want to spread the word. i am also grateful for my friends who helped me through hard times including through the time karl logan sexually harassed me via facebook and skype when i was 17. it has been a challenge for me but i was strong enough to fight against it. also this year i had my first partymonium in may and it was amazing to see all of my glam rock maniacs and party with them like it was 1985.
it was like a birthday party for me because my 18th birthday was may the 15th. also this year i got my driving license and my first car and had my first job going on, so many events. i am more grateful to have parents who support me in life and also entertain me with going to concerts with me like for example i went to see guns n roses with my dad this year. love him for that. i don't take their support for granted and so i don't take my friends' support for granted. i appreciate every single second with them. thanks for saving my year and made it a good one. ğŸ˜Š ğŸ–¤ sending love

text: i'm sitting here with tears in my brown eyes and a mind and heart trying to write this tribute to you sisters who still walk this beautiful, horrible world. i want all of you to understand why my tear-stained shirt a hurting sister was forced to sew me is still sticking to my clean and soiled and hydrated and dry skin. i'm trying to tell you why, since this dim sepia-ish photo was taken by one of my strong mamas on one of the most dazzling days of my life, i've metaphorically-and-literally-littered empty cardboard boxes, thin cotton cheap tees and sweaters, and countless pounds of tears and toxins from a strong and broken body. my eyes are tired because since this photo of me and two of my freshly-reborn sisters was taken, i've been humbled, favored, blessed and cursed to traverse a few more feet of this horrid and beautiful world. to still walk til my perfectly designed yet still imperfect, hurting body stops exuding passionate and exhausted life. i'm remembering why my heart that my big sister told me is like a fragile tiffany lamp got broken, again. i'm remembering  the week that made me tired in the best and worst ways i've lived. it was 8 days ago that all my mamas and all my big and fraternal twin and baby sisters told me they were honored hear me recite some of the book of my life. but after all my moms wrapped their arms right around me, held me next to their beautiful broken beating hearts, and cheered me on, i'm still aching for another warm hug from a perfect whole beating strong heart.  because i opened my eyes again, outside the walls of a safe, grace-filled home, and shut them tight.  and i can catch up on the news, but it would burn me like that bright sun and break my heart again. because i know far too many sisters of mine out there have text:
itâ€™s been a hard couple of weeks for so many of the women in my life, for so many people i love, for me. i did what i always do when iâ€™m trying to heal: i wrote. hereâ€™s some of it: â€œi am woman
all curves before age
i feel venus in the back of my throat as lyrics drip from lips on streets in ways that molest the most sacred parts of my body 
as fingers and hands grab in ways that never 
respected anything they caught
i am an object
less than human
only a woman
no words, no stories, no alibis 
no tears, no bruised bones 
she will never ever be enough
i wish i can wrap my arms around the beautiful black and brown bodies of my sisters
i want to slowly kiss away the bruises inside their gorgeous hearts
melting away the etched memories of wandering misogynist fingers and masculine sounds 
i want to wrap my baby sister in pre colonial matriarchy and femininity and self love and safety 
i just want her to be safe. 
before her eyes teach her to hate what she finds in the mirror
to seek affirmation in boys that never learned to love themselves
i wish i can heal myselfâ€

text:
@regrann from @agathaa.writes - * this post will be in hindi and english *
...
as girls, we all have gone through at least one situation where we have to prove-
arey bhai hum ladkiyan kum nahi hain. where we need to remind people and society, that before being a girl, i'm a human. ladki hona hota hai, ghar pe baithke yeh sikhna ki khana kaise banate hain? kapde kaise dhote hain?  ya shaadi kaise karte hain? 
if you think a girl is brought to this vast planet consisting billions of population, to serve one man at the stake of her own passion and dreams, then i would feel no shame in telling that you need to have a glass of wine and get a life. 
and the important thing is, kindly stop telling your daughters,  wives, mothers, sisters, girlfriends - basically your girls how they need to talk and sit and walk. and there's this one phase i am sure every girl reading this right now have faced. the stalker. 
i mean. stalk koi banda kar raha hai. pareshan vo banda kar raha hai. haddhein usse pata honi chahiye. par restrictions kispe lagte hain? you don't have to upload any of your photo. 
the most common reaction is-
why are you even on social media??? okay, so you mean just so that such assholes don't find a route to bother me, i should socially just isolate myself? so basically it's like. ladka jo karta hai karne do, tum chup rehkar baitho. i simply ask. why? uss stalker ne aisa kaunsa amrit ka pyaala piya hai jo uske liye hum chup rahein? he isn't a ruler. and i am not his subject. so stop teaching your girls how to accept defeat. tell them what a freaking power they are. make them realize that they are living in 21st century and they have the right to expression. 
and ek cheez jo mujhe abhi tak samajh nahi aayi. i have come across many people here. and most of them are influencers. either writers,  bloggers,  painters, artists, singers. you know, some kind of artists. and i really don't understand ki how does my face, my identity, my 'so-called beauty' is going to affect my art? man, i write that means i write.(-continued in comments-)

text:
to: built up emotions

i didn't want to to rock the boat

tip the thought

hear the gawk about

that

i didn't want to

see the clear 
view the mirror

reflecting back 
those truths

hitting home

beating deep

in my chest

i didn't want to wipe 
the floor

of the mess

leave it there

for the next

i didn't want that thing called pressure

to burst over

but it did

name: Hanni L
tweet_full:
to: built up emotions

i didn't want to to rock the boat

tip the thought

hear the gawk about

that

i didn't want to

see the clear 
view the mirror

reflecting back 
those truths

hitting home

beating deep

in my chest

i didn't want to wipe 
the floor

of the mess

leave it there

for the next

i didn't want that thing called pressure

to burst over

but it did

text:
eliza dushku has broken her silence in a powerful op-ed for the boston globe to repudiate what she describes as â€œrevisionist accountsâ€ put forth by cbs and former co-star michael weatherly, whom she accused of sexual harassment. cbs paid the actress a $9.5 million settlement, which was disclosed in a new york times report last week, to ensure her silence after she appeared for three episodes on the legal drama â€œbullâ€. she alleges series star weatherly made â€œcruelâ€ and â€œaggressiveâ€ jokes about sex, rape and her appearance in front of cast and crew members. 
dushku rejects the notion that her grievances arose from a misunderstanding between herself and weatherly, who apologized in a statement to the times, saying he was â€œmortifiedâ€ his sense of humor misfired. dushku, meanwhile, declined to comment in the bombshell report due to the conditions of the settlement. however, after weatherly and cbs did respond to the times, dushku says in wednesdayâ€™s op-ed, she decided to speak out. â€œi grew up in boston with three elder brothers and have generally been considered a tomboy. i made a name for myself playing a badass vampire slayer turned toughla cheerleader,â€ dushku writes. â€œi do not want to hear that i have a â€˜humor deficitâ€™ or canâ€™t take a joke. i did not over-react. i took a job and, because i did not want to be harassed, i was fired.â€ . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .  #elizadushku #equality #feminism #feminist #feminists #timesup #metoo #metoomovement #yesallwomen #fuckthepatriarchy  #smashthepatriarchy #yesallwomen #sexualharassment #harassment #sexualassault #feminism_around_the_world

text:
para reporter memilih 6 kontroversi paling buruk sepanjang tahun 2018

2018 adalah tahun dengan berbagai skandal di k-entertainment dengan banyak masalah kontroversial, tuntutan hukum, dan banyak lagi. sekarang dengan hanya beberapa minggu tersisa di tahun ini, wartawan dari sports today menyimpulkan orang-orang terburuk dengan kontroversi terburuk pada tahun 2018. siapa yang menurut para wartawan adalah yang terburuk tahun ini? lihatlah daftar di bawah ini:

1. yang hyun suk: pembatalan debut 'mixnine' "dengan kekuatan yg sebagai agensi, dia mengatakan dia akan membuat debut dan menempatkan peserta pelatihan dalam kompetisi, tetapi membatalkan debut mereka karena program itu gagal. dia menciptakan kontroversi dengan menanggapi geliat terakhir mereka mengambil tindakan hukum dengan gugatan balik. kemudian bahkan setahun kemudian, dia menciptakan acara audisi yang sama 'yg treasure box.' ide ironisnya mengejutkan semua orang. " - reporter yoon hye young.

2. lee seo won: pelecehan seksual "tingkah lakunya yang berani setelah pelecehan seksual, ketidaktahuan terus-menerus, dan terakhir, tindakan melarikan diri ke militer. aku terkejut 3 kali." - reporter kim sat byul

3. kim saeng min: #metoo "dia menghabiskan waktu emas yang ditunggu-tunggu dalam 25 tahun. kamu mendapatkan apa yang kamu berikan." - reporter kim na yeon

4. nancy lang x wang: pernikahan dan perceraian yang kontroversial "pembuat masalah dengan perkawinan, perkelahian, dan perceraian yang gaduh." - reporter han ye ji

5. lee jin min cp: manipulasi 'heart signal 2' "dia menciptakan program viral 'heart signal' tetapi ada juga banyak kontroversi. dia bahkan lebih mengecewakan penonton dengan perilakunya yang tidak menyenangkan dalam wawancara tentang kesalahan siaran, manipulasi dalam penyuntingan, dan banyak lagi." - reporter moon soo yeon

6. microdot: kasus lenipuan orang tua "orang tuanya berbohong kepada orang-orang di kota mereka, putranya berbohong kepada pemirsa." - reporter kim hyun min

source : allkpop, oh_mes
trans by : pink
Â©ksense

text:
todayâ€™s a big day of memories for me. 7 yrs ago today, i got engaged. i could say it was a happy time back then...but honestly even that day wasnâ€™t happy. i spent a portion of it crying, upset, didnâ€™t think my feelings were being considered. and yes, i was being hella dramatic. i literally put a fake engagement ring on &showed it to my boyfriend &told him i needed to wear it out because we had been dating for 6.5 years &it was long overdo. whoâ€™s dis crazy bitch? ğŸ¤ªğŸ˜‚ (for the record, i did not wear it out. ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚)
.
little did i know, heâ€™d be proposing later that night...and when it happened, i thought i was happy. this is what i had been waiting for! after so long together it was clearly the next step, right?
.
but what i wasnâ€™t thinking about that day was the time he wouldnâ€™t even look at me on my birthday, because he didnâ€™t like what i was wearing. or when he told me no one likes me because i always try to one-up people (iâ€™m pretty honest about my flaws, but that is not one of them...however it was one of his #gaslighting). or when he would get jealous and act crazy when i talked to other guys. and when he felt challenged by those guys and said, â€œhe can have youâ€...as if i was a prize to be won. iâ€™m ashamed to say all these things happened, and still i stayed.
.
real talk: in an emotionally abusive relationship, itâ€™s easy to say, â€œit wasnâ€™t my faultâ€, and thatâ€™s absolutely true. but hereâ€™s the part i do have to own up to...
.
i allowed it. .
my lack of boundaries invited him to disrespect me. itâ€™s like an enemy army rushing into a city and all of the soldiers are asleep instead of standing at the gate ready to protect their homes!
.
that part was my responsibility, and my own insecurities kept me from doing it well. it was something iâ€™d have to change if i ever wanted to move forward and heal. and i did.
.
so with this negative memory today, i thought iâ€™d make a better one - stay tuned for that announcement soon! .
if you made it this far, thank you for allowing me to share a snippet of my story. my hope is that by baring my soul, i can help even one girl to avoid what i did and realize she is worth so much more!â¤ï¸

text:
january 22, 2018 i had made a decision to â€œget outâ€. it was surprisingly the hardest yet easiest decision i have actually ever made in this life. i left an abusive relationship to learn more about love. i left a toxic relationship to build a stronger personal one with myself. i left a man to learn who i was needing to become as a woman. 
i left. i took very little. i took my babies. i cried. a lot. i struggled to get on my feet. i struggled to pay my bills. i was homeless for 4 months. i fought for a fair custody. i fought for a fair child support. i fought. and i continue to fight. 
i have learned that people will not approve of who you want to become based off of who you were. loving myself this year wasnâ€™t really a priority. i hated myself. i gained weight. i had tried to end my life a few times. i had fallen into a deep depression. i was living a stressed out, high anxiety, hateful life. and let me tell you something last night i had one of the most incredible evenings this year. 
i had a funeral for my failed relationship. i had a birthday celebration of my rebirth. today i woke up feeling a since of acceptance. my best friends surrounded me last night with love, laughter and their friendship.

thank you ladies for helping me celebrate a new beginning of this life. may the journey of self discovery and healing continue. 
#teamhalfbreed #70sinspired #rebirth #funeral #fuckdepression #anxiety #mentalhealthisreal #mentalhealth #battlingabattlenoonesees #behindasmile #metoo

i am excited to announce my second marie claire feature. i am in the january 2019 marie claire issue discussion female genital mutilation and my activism. it is great to reach new audiences and spread the message. my fgm work will have a new home in 2019. i am excited to do my work in a way that is true to my values of integrity, truth, human rights, diversity, inclusion, discrimination free zone, cultural integrity and pride embedded in intersectionality. there is no room for racism, double standards, white saviourism, islamophobia etc. 2018 has been a year of endings, closing chapters, dropping dead weight, cutting off toxic people, removing myself from roles and work spaces that were detrimental to my cultural rights, health, integrity and peace of mind. 2018 has been a year of being assertive and boy was i assertive ğŸ˜ğŸ˜‡ğŸ˜. assertive in all areas of my life. here is to 2019 and being true to myself in every way possible and continuing to kickass and be assertive. remember when one door closes another opens.

text:
â€ªthe way girls were raised (day 702)â€¬
*
*
*

her tiny paper voice redolent of old jewelry 
and longing, decorated with a fairytale ending, 
an act of real-life resistance, saying: â€œme too! my existence counts as something.â€ an umbrella, she sheds tears the clouds 
cry for the way girls were raised to run long, 
tapered fingers around wineglass rims, and 
to twirl the tiny paper parasols propped 
atop fruit-laden drinks with titillating names. 
how does she do itâ€”sing songs of such 
encouragement and evocation? yet, there, 
amidst a library of crumbling books in archaic languages, she hums a song so dark and cheerful 
that, in an unlit, unloved corner, goethe stirs 
and blinks approvingly, and she, sensing 
his presence, tosses him a knowing wink. *
*
* (c) 2018, by hannah six

itâ€™s a typical night at the frat house; booze are flowing, boobs are bouncing, and a young frat prodigy, rising through the ranks, is about to get lucky! to score major points with his frat bros and to avoid a humiliating pledge ritual, he leads a wasted sorority girl upstairs to swipe his v-card only to find out, getting lucky isn't as easy as it sounds. "guys at parties like it is a truly disturbing and heartbreaking exploration of the toxic masculinity pervasive in college campuses particularly with fraternity and sorority parties." -wescreenplay competition 
it has been reported that one in four women will experience sexual assault in their lifetime, including rape, molestation, coercion, and date rape. this story depicts the series of unfortunate events that lead to an all too common scenario about a girl, a boy, and the word "no". the #metoo and #timesup campaigns have taken hold of society in what can only be described as this generation's women's lib movement. it's these powerful stories of survival and strength that inspired the screenplay and are reshaping our world.

we understand that rape-revenge films are difficult to watch for a lot of survivors which is why we have decided not to include any graphic rape scenes throughout (but don't worry, there is tons of graphic gore.)

text:
what is life. i am officially a published author. ğŸ–Š

truly honored to be a part of this important collection of perspectives on equality & inclusion alongside some incredible asian leaders. âœŠğŸ¼ looking back on almost a decade of working in diversity in entertainment, my m nd is blown by how far weâ€™ve come in prioritizing & appreciating real, authentic stories from all walks of life - gender, race, sexuality, geography, generation. even though thereâ€™s much more work to do, itâ€™s encouraging to know that these topics matter now more than ever before. and weâ€™re all getting our heads out of the sand to be awake and active in the process. ğŸ§ 

iâ€™m continuing to learn just how much representation in entertainment plays out & interacts with every other industry (tech, finance, wellness, etc), including those of my brilliant co-authors. i know these ideas can slip away into just being lofty words or some stuffy soundbites.. but they affect our everyday lives & deserve recognition & our conscious investment. ğŸ‘¥ 
equality & inclusion influence the people we serve & the leaders we elect & the many systems that shape our careers, families, & relationships. they are crucial to pursue in any industry & weâ€™ll keep the movement going, one conversation at a time. ğŸ—£

the majority of proceeds from this book will go to the amazing @advancingjustice_aajc. thank you to @chiragdsagar & @askadamtorres for making this happen! find the book on #amazon along with everything else you buy in life. hope its a helpful resource to whoever finds it. ğŸ–Š ğŸ“¸: @thisisge

text:
it was a wild ride to financial independence retire early (fire). but at 35, i did it! 
there were several times when the emergency fund came in handy. 
in light of #metoo + #timesup, i was able to leave toxic work environments in a matter of days. 
i hope everyone in our community has an emergency fund in place. 
an emergency fund is also known as f-you money. 
hopefully you won't ever need to touch it! 
but if you do + end up sayin' f-you to the employer, i want to hear about it! 
either way, always love hearing about ppl's journey to fire.

my adventure continues as i aim to create wealth beyond money: 
https://www.notabondgirl.com/blog/how-i-reached-financial-independence-at-35

text:
it took me and is actually still taking me a long time to rebuild my self worth. for a long time i thought i was only worth the body i was in. merely a toy to be used as pleased, called when needed and told to shut up when i had an opinion of my own. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i sent four years trapped in a relationship where i was isolated from friends and family, watched, belittled, called crazy, stupid and emotional. i felt i couldnâ€™t leave the person i was with, i was total dependant on them. made to be, thatâ€™s the way they keep you trapped.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
people have often questioned why i didnâ€™t get out earlier. but i couldnâ€™t, my soul had been pushed out of me and iâ€™d been ground into dirt. nothing but a pile of worthless dirt. the day i did break it off, i had a full blown panic attack. that was one of the hardest days of my life. but that tiny second of light i saw was enough for me to get out.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
people can get great joy out of wearing a person down, and will just move onto the next victim. unfortunately for you, itâ€™s not so easy to say â€œnextâ€.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
my self worth will forever more be a battle i have to tackle. although it is much better, i still find in quite moments, questioning whether i still might just be a pile of dirt... ______________________________
